{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's poem *Shama* (\"The Candle\"), the speaker (personifying restless consciousness or the soul) reflects on exile from its divine origin. The key *couplet* (actually spanning two *sher*) fuses remembrance and yearning via *yaad-e-watan* (\"memory of the homeland\"):\n\n> Qaidi hoon aur qafas ko chaman jaanta hoon main  \n> Ghurbat ke gham-kade ko watan jaanta hoon main  \n> **Yaad e-watan fasurdagi-e-be-sabab bani**  \n> Shauq nazar kabhi, kabhi zauq-e-talab bani[^1]\n\n> A captive now, I call my cage a garden bright,  \n> This house of exile is my homeland and my light.  \n> **The memory of home became a causeless ache,**  \n> A thirst to see, a questing passion for its sake.[^2]\n\nHere, *yaad* is no inert record but a living torment: it *becomes* (*bani*) groundless pain (*fasurdagi-e-be-sabab*), visual longing (*shauq-e-nazar*), and acquisitive desire (*zauq-e-talab*). The homeland's *yaad* propels ceaseless striving, embodying Iqbal's metaphysics of dynamic selfhood—exile from the divine (*zaib darakht-e-Toor*, the burning bush of Sinai) fuels cosmic aspiration.[^3]\n\nTranslating *yaad* flatly as \"memory\" collapses the line: \"The memory of home became a causeless ache...\" detaches neutral cognition from its innate *pull* toward reunion. English forces the translator to graft on \"ache,\" \"thirst,\" and \"passion\" as add-ons, diluting *yaad*'s holistic throb of *recalling-to-possess*. The Urdu couples remembrance and absence's pang inseparably; \"memory\" alone evokes mere factuality, not the ache's urgency that births motion (*ishq* as propulsion).\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 40 (*Shama*), transliteration, [p-b0d063](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/40-shama/transliteration/#p-b0d063).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 40 (*Shama*), translation, [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/40-shama/translation/#p-f4425a#p-e73be2).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 40 (*Shama*), translation, [whole chapter](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/40-shama/translation/).",
